[5] Cholera - Mozambique (Sofala)
Date: Thu, 10 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Angola Press [edited]
<http://www.angolapress-angop.ao/noticia-e.asp?ID=390224>

Mozambique's cholera epidemic has claimed 4 more lives recently in
the central province of Sofala, and has spread to the locality of
Mbongola in the district of Buzi, where 2 new cases were diagnosed in
the last few days, the daily Noticias newspaper reported Wed, 9 Nov
2005.
A report presented on Tue, 8 Nov 2005, during the opening of a
Consultative Council of the Health Ministry in the city of Beira,
said that 4 more people died, bringing to 15 the number of deaths,
out of 820 cases notified in the province since the outbreak of the
disease in January 2005.
Beira alone has reported 150 cholera cases, but no deaths. Here, the
Nova-Praia suburb is the most affected due to poor sanitation
conditions, with very few of the 500 resident families having
latrines. Beira and Buzi are the only 2 regions still reporting
cholera cases, and Sofala provincial Health director Alberto Baptista
urged the participants to the meeting to redouble their efforts to
make sure that the disease is contained.
The health authorities, particularly worried because of the poor
sanitation conditions in most places where cholera cases were
reported, are renewing calls for preventive measures, with particular
attention to the consumption of fruits such as mangoes, which should
always be washed before they are eaten.
--
