[7] Cholera - Guam
Date: Fri, 11 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: KUAM.com [edited]
<http://www.kuam.com/news/15646.aspx>

Public Health officials announced the confirmation of cholera, a
disease contracted by drinking water containing fecal matter or
eating contaminated food, on Guam. While one case has been confirmed,
healthcare experts have launched an investigation but believe an
outbreak isn't likely.
Test results from diagnostic laboratory services in Hawaii confirm
Guam has a single case at this time. Public Health epidemiologist Dr.
Robert Haddock says a male adult patient treated for diarrhea at the
Guam Memorial Hospital earlier this week was confirmed to have the
disease. Tests were also conducted on 2 other patients with suspected
cholera. "They live in the same general area; they are not related,
but we're looking into the possibility that they may have had some
social contact between the different households," affirmed Haddock.
The patient with the disease lives with relatives who recently
returned from Chuuk. Dr. Haddock says the confirmation has prompted
officials to conduct an investigation with the Guam Environmental
Protection Agency, and Public Health's Environmental Health Division
and nurses. The focus will be to look into the problem and determine
how the cases spread. Continued Haddock, "We believe the present
problem is due to specific sanitation problems in one general area;
we don't believe there's much likelihood it will spread outside of
that area."
The Public Health epidemiologist says because Guam has an adequate
water supply, it's not likely that the island's water system would be
the source of any contamination. For now, he warns residents to take
precaution. "We would caution people as usual to avoid eating
uncooked or raw seafood, particularly if it's caught in the
near-shore areas; that's been a problem in the past," said the
physician.
According to Public Health's Office of Epidemiology and Research
[regarding] the disease outbreaks on the island, the last time there
was a confirmed case of cholera was 5 years ago. Back in 2000, Guam
had one confirmed case from Pohnpei, and 3 additional cases were
contracted on island in association with individuals who ate fish
imported from Pohnpei. Dr. Haddock confirms there have also been more
reported cases of parasitic worms that are contracted [in the same
way as] cholera. "Some of the doctors believe that we've had more
cases this year than previously," he told KUAM News.
While officials await the test results of the suspected cases, which
are expected sometime next week, Dr. Haddock says local physicians
have been advised to stay alert. "We've alerted the physicians to be
on the lookout for possible other cases. We don't expect there to be
any cases at the community at large, but we want them to be alert to
that possibility. At this time we don't believe that it's a threat to
the community at large, it's just a localized problem."
[Byline: Mindy Fothergill]
--
